and psychology as well.Sagar writes that, as things stand, there appear to be no good arguments for believing in the truth of basic equality. Indeed, for much of Western intellectual history and social practice, basic inequality has been the default position. How is it then, Sagar asks, that in Western societies, in a period of less than a century, basic equality emerged as the dominant view? Sagar approaches this not as a mere philosophical puzzle, but as a dramatic historical development. In so doing, he shows us what is at stake when human beings treat one another as equals just because they are human beings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEqualityxPhilosophy. 0aEqualityxPolitical aspects. 0aEquality. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aBasic Equality.  aBernard Williams.  aDavid Hume.  aEquality.  aJeremy Waldron.  aJohn Rawls.  aPaul Sagar.  aPrinceton University Press.  abasic equality.  abooks.  aequality of opportunity.  aequity.  aessences.  afairness.  agenealogy.  ahistory.  ajustice.  ameritocracy.  amoral equality.  aprogress.  apsychology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691257792?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691257792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691257792/original  a978-3-11-074975-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles